    "body": "### Problem\n\n`:help shell-powershell` recommends some settings for use with powershell. It includes this line that implies it works for both legacy powershell (v5?) and new pwsh (v7+?):\n```vim\nlet &shell = executable('pwsh') ? 'pwsh' : 'powershell'\n```\n\nHowever, it produces errors when using those settings on a machine that has powershell and not pwsh (the default for new Windows installs):\n```\n:echo 'powershell' executable('powershell') 'pwsh' executable('pwsh')\npowershell 1 pwsh 0\n\n:!echo 1\nThe property 'OutputRendering' cannot be found on this object. Verify that the property exists and can be set.\nAt line:1 char:140\n+ ... t-File:Encoding']='utf8';$PSStyle.OutputRendering='plaintext';Remove- ...\n+                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n    + CategoryInfo          : InvalidOperation: (:) [], RuntimeException\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : PropertyNotFound\n \nRemove-Alias : The term 'Remove-Alias' is not recognized as the name of a cmdlet, function, script file, or operable \nprogram. Check the spelling of the name, or if a path was included, verify that the path is correct and try again.\nAt line:1 char:177\n+ ... ng']='utf8';$PSStyle.OutputRendering='plaintext';Remove-Alias -Force  ...\n+                                                      ~~~~~~~~~~~~\n    + CategoryInfo          : ObjectNotFound: (Remove-Alias:String) [], CommandNotFoundException\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException\n \n1\n```\n\nI suspect most of the settings are only valid for pwsh. If I remove the options it complains about then it seems to work:\n```\nlet &shellcmdflag = '-NoLogo -NonInteractive -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Command [Console]::InputEncoding=[Console]::OutputEncoding=[System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new();$PSDefaultParameterValues[''Out-File:Encoding'']=''utf8'';'\n```\nAlthough omitting `Remove-Alias` is probably doing something subtly wrong? \n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n\n\nnvim --clean -u ~/config_shell.vim\n```\n\" From :help shell-powershell\nlet &shell = executable('pwsh') ? 'pwsh' : 'powershell'\nlet &shellcmdflag = '-NoLogo -NonInteractive -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Command [Console]::InputEncoding=[Console]::OutputEncoding=[System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new();$PSDefaultParameterValues[''Out-File:Encoding'']=''utf8'';$PSStyle.OutputRendering=''plaintext'';Remove-Alias -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue tee;'\nlet &shellredir = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | Out-File %s; exit $LastExitCode'\nlet &shellpipe  = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | tee %s; exit $LastExitCode'\nset shellquote= shellxquote=\n```\n\nVerify you only have powershell and not pwsh:\n```\n:echo 'powershell' executable('powershell') 'pwsh' executable('pwsh')\npowershell 1 pwsh 0\n```\n\nThen run `:! echo 1` and you should see errors.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe docs only recommend settings that work.\n\nProbably, we should document `pwsh` and push users to a single well-supported solution. ie., `let &shell = 'pwsh'` and point to [the installer](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/scripting/install/install-powershell-on-windows) or [project](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.11.5\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWin11 (Microsoft Windows [Version 10.0.26200.7462])\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nCommand Prompt\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nnot set\n\n### Installation\n\nscoop",
